on of food and labor have been felt as strongly in China as anywhere—and yet, as Schmalzer shows, Mao-era challenges to technocracy laid important groundwork for today’s sustainability and food justice movements. This history of “scientific farming” in China offers us a unique opportunity not only to explore the consequences of modern agricultural technologies but also to engage in a necessary rethinking of fundamental assumptions about science and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculture and statezChina. 0aCommunism and agriculture. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience, scientific, farm, farming, work, socialism, socialist, government, theory, theoretical, china, chinese, asia, asian, eastern, far east, usaid, 1960s, green, revolutionary, change, hunger, starving, activism, aid, help, modernization, contemporary, modern, agriculture, environmental, mao, era, time period, justice, injustice, academic, scholarly, research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022633015040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226330297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226330297/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles